=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

But when it comes to specific questions about how he=E2=80=99s handling the=
 economy and
inflation, the president is on much shakier ground with young men. Della Vo=
lpe gave me an exclusive look at his SocialSphere polling between mid-Janua=
ry and mid-February. In January, 62 percent of men under 30 approved of Tru=
mp=E2=80=99s handling of the economy. Now, just 48 percent approve=E2=80=94=
a drop of 14 points in just one month. On handling inflation, Trump has tak=
en a 15-point hit, dropping from 55 percent approval before the inauguratio=
n to just 40 percent today. And those downward trends are from
Della Volpe=E2=80=99s February poll, which was in the field two weeks ago=
=E2=80=94before multiple news cycles about nagging inflation, before tariff=
s sent the markets spiraling, before egg prices hit an all-time record ( ht=
tps://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/APU0000708111?utm_campaign=3DThe+Best+%26+=
The+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F4%2F25%29&utm_content=3DThe+Best+%26+The=
+Brightest+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%283%2F3%2F25%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sou=
rce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ), and before Bitcoin and o=
ther cryptocurrencies took a massive hit. =E2=80=9CTrump=E2=80=99s favorabi=
lity among young men remains relatively steady, masking their growing skept=
icism about his economic
policies and handling of inflation just a month into his presidency,=E2=80=
=9D Della Volpe told me. =E2=80=9CWomen have already broken with him. If li=
fe doesn=E2=80=99t become more affordable as Trump promised, and quickly, e=
ven his strongest backers may conclude he can=E2=80=99t deliver.=E2=80=9D

Portnoy=E2=80=99s
Complaint
-----------

Still, Della Volpe said, many young men are inclined to give Trump the bene=
fit of the
doubt. He shared with me two quotes from a recent focus group he conducted =
with young men who didn=E2=80=99t go to college and voted for Trump. Both h=
ad to do with the economy. One participant, a white man, was asked why he=
=E2=80=99s optimistic about Trump: =E2=80=9CI said =E2=80=98optimistic=E2=
=80=99 mainly for the fact that I=E2=80=99m going to be moving up with my j=
ob, and I=E2=80=99m hoping that Trump can fix the economy.=E2=80=9D Another=
, a young Hispanic male, said he=E2=80=99s going to give Trump more time to=
 deliver: =E2=80=9CWith the previous president, I was
genuinely scared for my country. I am a Democrat, but I think President Tru=
mp=E2=80=99s policies and goals are what America needs in order to be succe=
ssful=E2=80=94as unfortunate as that sounds. That=E2=80=99s just where I am=
 with it. I feel now there is a little bit more hope now we have President =
Trump in office.=E2=80=9D

Those perspectives on Trump=E2=80=94a little financial anxiety, leavened by=
 a wait-and-see attitude=E2=80=94sounded a bit like Dave Portnoy during an =
appearance on the Fox Business Channel last week. Host
Stuart Varney asked Portnoy to score Trump=E2=80=99s presidency so far. His=
 response, I think, conveyed what a lot of young men who voted for Trump ha=
ve been thinking lately: Chill with the culture war stuff, thank you very m=
uch, and stay focused on the bottom line. =E2=80=9CObviously, this Epstein =
list is a circus. I don=E2=80=99t know what they were doing walking out wit=
h those binders. That was stupid,=E2=80=9D Portnoy said, referring to the b=
otched stunt in which A.G. Pam Bondi hyped up
the release of bombshell new Epstein documents, only to release information=
 that had been publicly available for years. =E2=80=9CBut overall, [Trump=
=E2=80=99s] doing what he said he was going to do. I am a very simple man, =
Stuart. I like it when my stocks are going up and my wallet is getting fatt=
er. Right now, it=E2=80=99s going the reverse way, so you start to raise an=
 eyebrow. But overall? I=E2=80=99m happy.=E2=80=9D

