;Inter&#39;,&#39;Arial&#39;;font-size:17px;font-weight:400;letter-spacing:0=
px;line-height:150%;text-align:left;mso-line-height-alt:25.5px;"><p style=
=3D"margin:0;">I did a gut check with a smart Democratic operative who thin=
ks the party should do
more to reach normies and not just nerds. The source texted me back in all =
caps: =E2=80=9CATTENTION ECONOMY!=E2=80=9D And he=E2=80=99s right. The vide=
o barrage showed Beltway Democrats <em>finally</em> getting it and stealing=
 from the media playbook that Trump and his allies have mastered. Here were=
 a bunch of crusty senators forgetting their senatorial dignity for a minut=
e and doing something that got people talking=E2=80=94embracing vertical vi=
deo over television and realizing that generating attention for attention=
=E2=80=99s sake
is how you put points on the board in today=E2=80=99s media world.<br/><br/=
>By sharing and broadcasting the videos, Musk, LibsOfTikTok, =E2=80=9CBased=
=E2=80=9D Mike Lee and all the rest were inadvertently doing the Democrats=
=E2=80=99 bidding: Elevating an anti-Trump message about high prices and a =
sputtering economy to many millions more than would have seen it otherwise.=
 Already, the videos have gotten close to a combined 3 million views across=
 each senator=E2=80=99s social media accounts=E2=80=94and millions more els=
ewhere thanks to Musk, Fox
News, and other Trump supporters who broadcast them today. All those media =
impressions hit at the exact moment Trump=E2=80=99s newest tariffs sent the=
 market skidding and gave commodity prices a jolt. <br/><br/>In a way, the =
effort was the reverse image of what Democrats and journalists have done fo=
r years in the Trump era by screenshotting and reposting outrageous claims =
and disinformation peddled by Trump and his allies. Animated by self-righte=
ousness, they were also=E2=80=94oops!=E2=80=94giving a lift to all that fak=
e
news and accidentally catapulting those messages far beyond their original =
spaces and networks. With respect to <strong>Elissa Slotkin</strong>, who w=
as tapped to deliver the Democrats=E2=80=99 official response to Trump=E2=
=80=99s speech, many more people will see one of these clips than will tune=
 in to watch what the freshman senator from Michigan will have to say this =
evening.<br/><br/>The video effort was organized by <strong>Cory Booker</st=
rong>, a prolific purveyor of selfie videos who, by his own admission,
can be a little cringe in his own earnest Gen X way. Booker is still years =
younger than most of the Senate, and with the help of some aides and consul=
tants, he=E2=80=99s running the Senate Democrats=E2=80=99 Strategic Communi=
cations Committee, advising his colleagues on how to reach voters on the sm=
all screen, where they actually spend their time. =E2=80=9CThe bottom line =
is that it drew attention to our message today, which is that Donald Trump =
is looking out for billionaires, not regular people,=E2=80=9D Booker told m=
e over
the phone a few hours ago, chuckling about how Musk gave the videos a mega-=
boost. =E2=80=9CIt shows that we can do their playbook just as well, which =
is to use our ecosystem of connected progressive voices to get a single mes=
sage out. Trump doesn=E2=80=99t often care about the details of how he gets=
 his message out, he just wants to monopolize attention. And today we drew =
a lot of attention as well.=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>Booker gave his Senate collea=
gues credit for experimenting. =E2=80=9CInstead of leaving this as a platfo=
rm for
staff, they are creators now,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re ho=
lding their own camera, speaking directly to the camera, finding creative h=
ooks, really learning and actually becoming pretty good at it.=E2=80=9D<br/=
><br/>Members of the Senate Democratic Caucus, of course, aren=E2=80=99t su=
ddenly going to become memelords and ring light masters overnight. We=E2=80=
=99re talking about <strong>Sheldon Whitehouse</strong> and <strong>Mazie H=
irono</strong>, after all. One Democratic operative I talked to joked: =E2=
=80=9CI guess you go to war with
the lame nerds you have!=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>I relayed this sentiment to Book=
er. He admitted that Democrats on the Hill will never reach <strong>Alix Ea=
rle</strong> or <strong>David Dobrik</strong> status, but said he=E2=80=99s=
 confident that his colleagues are starting to understand that these days t=
he phone is more powerful than a cable news hit. =E2=80=9CBefore, we weren=
=E2=80=99t even on the playing field,=E2=80=9D Booker said. =E2=80=9CWe wer=
en=E2=80=99t even competing in the new media space. We went from a standsti=
ll to walking at a brisk pace, but
look, you have to walk before you can run, and you gotta run before you can=
 soar.=E2=80=9D Musk, it appears, will have to send that Cyber Truck to Boo=
ker=E2=80=99s place in Newark.</p></div>
